1
00:00:02,840 --> 00:00:09,810
[screaming and explosions]

2
00:00:09,850 --> 00:00:15,070
♪

3
00:00:15,120 --> 00:00:19,210
- Look at them praying for
a miracle that isn't coming.

4
00:00:19,250 --> 00:00:22,170
Who knows, maybe it's my curse

5
00:00:22,210 --> 00:00:24,390
to leave one betrayal behind,

6
00:00:24,430 --> 00:00:28,310
only to find a greater one
here amongst the stars?

7
00:00:28,350 --> 00:00:31,090
They could've stopped this,

8
00:00:31,130 --> 00:00:32,920
but none of them
had the strength to do

9
00:00:32,960 --> 00:00:34,440
what must be done,

10
00:00:34,490 --> 00:00:37,100
but I do.

11
00:00:37,140 --> 00:00:38,660
♪

12
00:00:38,710 --> 00:00:39,930
[whirring]

13
00:00:39,970 --> 00:00:47,020
♪

14
00:01:14,610 --> 00:01:17,400
- So what's it like walking
to go get coffee

15
00:01:17,440 --> 00:01:19,970
when you can run
4,000 miles an hour?

16
00:01:20,010 --> 00:01:21,790
- It's nice slowing down
every once and a while,

17
00:01:21,840 --> 00:01:23,060
even for the Flash.

18
00:01:23,100 --> 00:01:24,930
Is Frost joining us?
- No.

19
00:01:24,970 --> 00:01:27,630
Last night I sent her on a
two-week "Eat, Pray, Love" tour

20
00:01:27,670 --> 00:01:30,150
because she's still
pining over Mark Blaine.

21
00:01:30,190 --> 00:01:31,850
- I thought she was
mad at him all summer.

22
00:01:31,890 --> 00:01:34,410
- And fall,
but she still misses him

23
00:01:34,460 --> 00:01:35,890
even though I told her

24
00:01:35,940 --> 00:01:37,720
he's a jerk who is
never gonna change.

25
00:01:37,770 --> 00:01:39,070
- Let me guess,
she didn't care?

26
00:01:39,120 --> 00:01:40,420
- Yep, she said,

27
00:01:40,460 --> 00:01:42,420
"The heart wants
what the heart wants."

28
00:01:42,470 --> 00:01:44,210
- She's always been
such a romantic.

29
00:01:50,080 --> 00:01:51,610
- I have learned one thing

30
00:01:51,650 --> 00:01:53,390
watching Frost
go through all of this.

31
00:01:53,430 --> 00:01:57,740
For the first time
since Ronnie passed,

32
00:01:57,790 --> 00:01:59,790
I think I'm really ready
to get back out there.

33
00:02:01,490 --> 00:02:03,570
I'm gonna start dating again.

34
00:02:03,620 --> 00:02:06,010
- That's awesome.
I'm really happy for you.

35
00:02:06,050 --> 00:02:07,670
- Thank you.

36
00:02:07,710 --> 00:02:09,410
Now, if I could just get
some oat milk for my coffee.

37
00:02:09,450 --> 00:02:12,240
[phone rings]

38
00:02:12,280 --> 00:02:13,850
- Two bullet trains
on the Calvert railway

39
00:02:13,890 --> 00:02:15,240
are gonna collide.
- Barry,

40
00:02:15,280 --> 00:02:16,720
that's 50 miles south
of Keystone City.

41
00:02:16,760 --> 00:02:17,760
- Yeah.

42
00:02:17,810 --> 00:02:20,160
[dramatic music]

43
00:02:20,200 --> 00:02:23,160
[train horns blaring]

44
00:02:23,200 --> 00:02:30,210
♪

45
00:02:37,090 --> 00:02:39,570
- Ladies and gentlemen,
authorities are now confirming

46
00:02:39,610 --> 00:02:41,700
that despite
a massive explosion,

47
00:02:41,740 --> 00:02:44,310
caused by
today's railway accident,

48
00:02:44,350 --> 00:02:48,530
no lives were lost during
this horrific event.

49
00:02:48,580 --> 00:02:52,280
It appears our city has
the Flash to thank once more.

50
00:02:54,930 --> 00:02:57,320
- That was amazing.

51
00:02:57,370 --> 00:03:00,240
You got everyone to safety
in what, 20 seconds?

52
00:03:00,280 --> 00:03:01,890
- 12, actually.

53
00:03:01,940 --> 00:03:02,980
Try your coffee.

54
00:03:03,020 --> 00:03:08,380
♪

55
00:03:08,420 --> 00:03:11,420
- Wow, you have seriously
leveled up.

56
00:03:11,470 --> 00:03:13,600
If only you could teach Frost
how to do the same.

57
00:03:13,640 --> 00:03:16,690
I mean, bypassing anyone who
calls themselves Chillblaine,

58
00:03:16,730 --> 00:03:18,390
I think, would save
for a lot of heartbreak.

59
00:03:18,430 --> 00:03:21,430
- I mean, Frost dating anybody
is a first for her.

60
00:03:21,480 --> 00:03:24,180
Right? And everybody you dated
before Ronnie,

61
00:03:24,220 --> 00:03:25,830
I'm guessing,
that was you leveling up.

62
00:03:25,870 --> 00:03:28,010
You know, it's a process.

63
00:03:28,050 --> 00:03:30,570
Maybe just give Frost
space to do the same.

64
00:03:30,620 --> 00:03:33,270
♪

65
00:03:33,320 --> 00:03:34,930
- Captain Kramer,
while supportive

66
00:03:34,970 --> 00:03:37,840
of your transparency,
you have been criticized

67
00:03:37,890 --> 00:03:40,450
for your decision to disband
the city's meta-task force.

68
00:03:40,500 --> 00:03:41,980
Some people thinking
that it will

69
00:03:42,020 --> 00:03:44,240
increase meta-crime
across the city.

70
00:03:44,280 --> 00:03:45,720
Do you care to comment?

71
00:03:45,760 --> 00:03:49,070
- Once I came to terms
with being a meta,

72
00:03:49,110 --> 00:03:52,290
it helped me realize
how important it is

73
00:03:52,340 --> 00:03:55,120
for everyone
in Central City to receive

74
00:03:55,160 --> 00:03:57,040
equal protections
under the same laws.

75
00:03:57,080 --> 00:03:59,820
- So you felt as though
the meta-task force

76
00:03:59,860 --> 00:04:01,430
was unfairly targeting

77
00:04:01,470 --> 00:04:03,040
marginalized sections
of the populace.

78
00:04:03,080 --> 00:04:04,350
- Yes.

79
00:04:04,390 --> 00:04:06,090
Which is why
its time has passed.

80
00:04:06,130 --> 00:04:08,390
- All right, thank you,
Captain Kramer.

81
00:04:08,440 --> 00:04:10,960
This is Iris West-Allen
for "Citizentopia."

82
00:04:11,010 --> 00:04:12,180
Thank you for listening.

83
00:04:13,530 --> 00:04:14,840
That was great.
- [sighs]

84
00:04:14,880 --> 00:04:16,320
- It was great. Come in.

85
00:04:16,360 --> 00:04:18,750
Allegra, you remember
Captain Kramer.

86
00:04:18,800 --> 00:04:20,150
- Hi.

87
00:04:20,190 --> 00:04:22,100
Well, I'll--I
have an appointment

88
00:04:22,150 --> 00:04:24,280
with Chief Singh, so...thanks.

89
00:04:25,720 --> 00:04:27,410
- You wanted to see me?

90
00:04:27,460 --> 00:04:31,240
- Yes, so the last six months
have been pretty intense.

91
00:04:31,290 --> 00:04:33,810
- I'll say.
We have three new reporters,

92
00:04:33,850 --> 00:04:36,340
an IT intern, and
an office manager now.

93
00:04:36,380 --> 00:04:38,900
Plus, online circulation's
over two million,

94
00:04:38,950 --> 00:04:41,040
and your new podcast
is frickin' brilliant.

95
00:04:41,080 --> 00:04:42,600
- Thank you.
- Oh,

96
00:04:42,650 --> 00:04:44,130
we need faster Internet.

97
00:04:44,170 --> 00:04:45,740
Should we call
the new landlord?

98
00:04:45,780 --> 00:04:47,260
- Sue Dearbon bought
the building.

99
00:04:47,300 --> 00:04:49,260
I think we can fix
our own Internet.

100
00:04:49,310 --> 00:04:50,870
- Roger that,

101
00:04:50,920 --> 00:04:52,830
but seriously, I just don't see
how you do it all

102
00:04:52,870 --> 00:04:54,400
and still find time
for an op-ed each week.

103
00:04:54,440 --> 00:04:56,010
- Well, I can't.

104
00:04:56,050 --> 00:04:58,270
So the bullpen needs
a supervising editor,

105
00:04:58,310 --> 00:04:59,970
someone who decides
which stories we cover

106
00:05:00,010 --> 00:05:02,450
and then assigns
and pre-edits copy,

107
00:05:02,490 --> 00:05:06,450
which is why
I am promoting you.

108
00:05:06,500 --> 00:05:09,760
- Wh--Iris...
[stammers]

109
00:05:09,800 --> 00:05:11,630
I've barely
been staff for a year.

110
00:05:11,680 --> 00:05:13,550
I--I'm not ready for that.

111
00:05:13,590 --> 00:05:15,200
- Well, I think you are.

112
00:05:15,240 --> 00:05:16,940
- Well, you do realize you
have people on staff now

113
00:05:16,980 --> 00:05:19,600
who are more qualified
to handle that sort of thing.

114
00:05:19,640 --> 00:05:21,290
I mean, Vanya?

115
00:05:21,340 --> 00:05:23,080
She's got 10 years of
experience under her belt.

116
00:05:23,120 --> 00:05:25,650
Or that annoying Taylor
just graduated summa cum laude

117
00:05:25,690 --> 00:05:28,040
from Barnard College.
Even the old guy

118
00:05:28,080 --> 00:05:29,610
was a war correspondent
in Beirut.

119
00:05:29,650 --> 00:05:31,830
- Aariz is my age.

120
00:05:32,780 --> 00:05:33,740
Girl.

121
00:05:33,780 --> 00:05:37,700
♪

122
00:05:37,740 --> 00:05:40,400
Look, now that
we're CC Citizen Media,

123
00:05:40,440 --> 00:05:43,360
I am busier with more
and more administrative duties.

124
00:05:43,400 --> 00:05:44,970
- Iris, are you sure?

125
00:05:45,010 --> 00:05:47,490
- You got this.
I believe in you.

126
00:05:47,540 --> 00:05:52,370
♪

127
00:05:52,410 --> 00:05:54,070
What is this?

128
00:05:54,110 --> 00:05:56,810
- A candlelit pizza dinner

129
00:05:56,850 --> 00:05:58,240
from our favorite place
in Milan.

130
00:05:58,290 --> 00:06:01,590
- Oh, thank God.
I was too tired to cook.

131
00:06:01,640 --> 00:06:03,160
- I can't imagine why.

132
00:06:03,200 --> 00:06:05,900
Team Citizen has been
in overdrive these days.

133
00:06:05,950 --> 00:06:08,080
Plus, Deon's still
helping to stabilize

134
00:06:08,120 --> 00:06:10,650
your temporal sickness
with regular treatments.

135
00:06:10,690 --> 00:06:12,390
It's a lot to handle.

136
00:06:12,430 --> 00:06:13,740
- I told you, I'm fine.

137
00:06:13,780 --> 00:06:15,090
Plus, you're not exactly

138
00:06:15,130 --> 00:06:16,740
an underachiever yourself,
Flash.

139
00:06:16,780 --> 00:06:19,180
Nice work at Calvert Railway.
- Thanks.

140
00:06:19,220 --> 00:06:20,700
- I guess we both
earned a night off.

141
00:06:20,740 --> 00:06:22,180
- And without kids too.

142
00:06:22,220 --> 00:06:23,920
I mean, don't get me wrong,
it's great

143
00:06:23,960 --> 00:06:26,140
having Bart and Nora stop in
all the time from 2049.

144
00:06:26,180 --> 00:06:28,230
- But if we're ever
gonna have a baby...

145
00:06:28,270 --> 00:06:29,620
- Uh-huh.

146
00:06:29,670 --> 00:06:31,060
- We need some alone time,
Mr. Allen.

147
00:06:31,100 --> 00:06:32,410
- Mm-hmm.

148
00:06:32,450 --> 00:06:34,060
[knock on door]

149
00:06:35,190 --> 00:06:36,800
- Great.
- Yeah.

150
00:06:38,330 --> 00:06:40,850
Ray?
- In the flesh.

151
00:06:42,110 --> 00:06:44,990
- What--what brings you
to Central City?

152
00:06:45,030 --> 00:06:46,810
- Oh, well you guys said
I could always crash here

153
00:06:46,860 --> 00:06:50,080
if ever I was in town,
and I'm here attending CCTC,

154
00:06:50,120 --> 00:06:53,210
but my hotel was overbooked.
And it's impossible

155
00:06:53,250 --> 00:06:55,130
to get a conference hotel room
at the last minute.

156
00:06:55,170 --> 00:06:58,130
So I figured I'd take you up
on your very kind offer.

157
00:06:58,170 --> 00:07:00,830
- Oh, that makes sense.
- Does it?

158
00:07:02,090 --> 00:07:04,220
- Are you guys having pizza?
- Um...

159
00:07:04,270 --> 00:07:05,480
- Is it gluten free?

160
00:07:05,530 --> 00:07:08,230
- No, it's from Italy.
- Oh.

161
00:07:08,270 --> 00:07:10,100
- So where is Nora?

162
00:07:10,140 --> 00:07:11,360
Did she come with you?

163
00:07:11,400 --> 00:07:12,970
- No, she's saving the world

164
00:07:13,010 --> 00:07:14,710
one kid at a time
and loving it.

165
00:07:16,890 --> 00:07:19,500
Am...am I interrupting?

166
00:07:19,540 --> 00:07:21,240
- No.
- Never.

167
00:07:21,280 --> 00:07:22,760
- Really? Great!

168
00:07:22,810 --> 00:07:24,550
So is this a sofa bed,

169
00:07:24,590 --> 00:07:26,330
or, like, a sheets and blankets
on top sort of thing?

170
00:07:27,380 --> 00:07:30,030
- Uh, there is a guest bedroom
at the top of the stairs.

171
00:07:30,070 --> 00:07:32,560
- Ah, you guys are the best.

172
00:07:32,600 --> 00:07:34,510
I'll get the rest
of my bags later.

173
00:07:34,560 --> 00:07:35,990
both: Okay.

174
00:07:38,040 --> 00:07:39,560
- I thought
he could shrink things.

175
00:07:39,610 --> 00:07:41,130
- Yeah.

176
00:07:42,910 --> 00:07:44,220
- Truck's at the loading dock.

177
00:07:44,260 --> 00:07:45,610
- Copy that.

178
00:07:45,660 --> 00:07:47,090
Transport team's here.

179
00:07:48,700 --> 00:07:49,880
What the hell?

180
00:07:49,920 --> 00:07:56,970
♪

181
00:08:01,190 --> 00:08:03,060
- In three seconds,
the two on the outside

182
00:08:03,110 --> 00:08:04,760
will draw their weapons
and advance

183
00:08:04,800 --> 00:08:07,020
while the other two
hold their positions.

184
00:08:07,070 --> 00:08:09,240
Jack, you're up.

185
00:08:09,290 --> 00:08:10,510
[whirring]

186
00:08:10,550 --> 00:08:12,860
[groaning]

187
00:08:12,900 --> 00:08:15,340
- I could've melted
your faces instead.

188
00:08:15,380 --> 00:08:17,300
Guess you drew a lucky hand.

189
00:08:18,340 --> 00:08:20,560
- Ooh, their minds
are full of fear, Ten.

190
00:08:20,600 --> 00:08:22,950
Show them who
has the winning hand.

191
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:25,300
[groaning]

192
00:08:25,350 --> 00:08:26,870
♪

193
00:08:26,910 --> 00:08:28,130
- Jackpot.

194
00:08:28,180 --> 00:08:29,440
- Oh, crap.

195
00:08:29,480 --> 00:08:32,140
- My King, you know the drill.

196
00:08:34,180 --> 00:08:35,970
[groaning]

197
00:08:36,010 --> 00:08:41,750
♪

198
00:08:43,230 --> 00:08:45,720
- Guess he folded.
- Well, that's no fun.

199
00:08:45,760 --> 00:08:51,590
- Either way,
that was damn fine work,

200
00:08:51,630 --> 00:08:54,030
my Queen.

201
00:08:54,070 --> 00:08:55,590
- Well it's easy

202
00:08:55,640 --> 00:08:57,730
when you can see each card
before it's dealt.

203
00:08:59,600 --> 00:09:00,600
- My Queen.

204
00:09:02,380 --> 00:09:09,430
♪

205
00:09:12,740 --> 00:09:14,310
- Now what?

206
00:09:16,050 --> 00:09:17,660
- We raise the stakes.

207
00:09:25,800 --> 00:09:27,370
- There you go, Iris.

208
00:09:28,540 --> 00:09:31,720
- Uh, Ray, how often
do you talk to Sara

209
00:09:31,760 --> 00:09:33,330
and all the other Legends?

210
00:09:33,370 --> 00:09:35,630
- Well, not very often.

211
00:09:35,680 --> 00:09:38,810
Nate and I do have a standing
drinks night once a month,

212
00:09:38,860 --> 00:09:42,340
but he's rarely
in the same century or year.

213
00:09:42,380 --> 00:09:44,770
Yeah, that may be why I haven't
heard from him lately.

214
00:09:44,820 --> 00:09:47,340
- I'm sorry.
- It's okay.

215
00:09:47,390 --> 00:09:49,040
Kind of.

216
00:09:49,080 --> 00:09:51,650
Yeah, it was really hard
leaving the Legends,

217
00:09:51,690 --> 00:09:56,610
but since then, Nora and I have
been more connected than ever.

218
00:09:56,660 --> 00:09:58,830
And, uh, you know
I've been able to

219
00:09:58,880 --> 00:10:01,750
get back to my other true love,
pure research.

220
00:10:01,790 --> 00:10:03,970
Plus, my life's
more balanced now.

221
00:10:04,010 --> 00:10:06,620
It's not just, "I'm the Atom"
and science takes a backseat.

222
00:10:06,670 --> 00:10:08,670
You know?
So uh, yeah.

223
00:10:08,710 --> 00:10:10,060
To, uh--to second acts.

224
00:10:11,020 --> 00:10:11,980
[knock on door]

225
00:10:12,020 --> 00:10:13,190
both: I'll get it.

226
00:10:15,590 --> 00:10:18,500
- This year's legacy honoree
in the house.

227
00:10:18,550 --> 00:10:19,680
- Hey, Chester, yeah.
Come on in.

228
00:10:19,720 --> 00:10:20,980
- Okay.

229
00:10:21,030 --> 00:10:22,940
- Chester, Ray.
Ray, Chester.

230
00:10:22,990 --> 00:10:25,680
- Ah, so you're
the new team tech genius.

231
00:10:25,730 --> 00:10:27,430
Nice to meet you, Chester.

232
00:10:27,470 --> 00:10:29,250
- Likewise.
I've been a big fan of yours

233
00:10:29,300 --> 00:10:31,170
ever since reading
your papers on quantum qubits.

234
00:10:31,210 --> 00:10:33,560
- So you're pretty stoked
about the Con this year, huh?

235
00:10:33,610 --> 00:10:35,090
- Oh, are you kidding me?

236
00:10:35,130 --> 00:10:36,910
Ever since I found out
you were gonna be

237
00:10:36,960 --> 00:10:38,960
this year's legacy honoree,
I, kind of, took the liberty

238
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:42,220
of signing up
to be the CCTC volunteer.

239
00:10:43,660 --> 00:10:46,530
I'm gonna be your liaison
for the entire event.

240
00:10:46,570 --> 00:10:48,710
If that's--if that's cool?
Like, if you're--

241
00:10:48,750 --> 00:10:50,800
like, if you're all right?
- Sounds great.

242
00:10:50,840 --> 00:10:52,490
- Cool 'cause I already have

243
00:10:52,540 --> 00:10:53,930
your whole itinerary planned
to sweet perfection.

244
00:10:56,060 --> 00:10:58,630
- So um, I'm late for work.

245
00:10:58,670 --> 00:11:01,720
So Ray, Chester, I'll pop
by the convention center later.

246
00:11:01,760 --> 00:11:03,420
See ya. I gotta go.
- Don't you dare.

247
00:11:04,640 --> 00:11:07,680
[groans]
- Ah, he forgot his breakfast.

248
00:11:08,550 --> 00:11:09,900
- And that's a bracelet.

249
00:11:09,950 --> 00:11:11,160
Uh, you know what?
I have to go, too.

250
00:11:11,210 --> 00:11:12,560
[laughs]
Deadlines.

251
00:11:12,600 --> 00:11:14,080
Uh, you got
the list of questions

252
00:11:14,120 --> 00:11:15,730
for the interview later, right?
- Sure do.

253
00:11:15,780 --> 00:11:17,000
See you at 4:00.

254
00:11:20,610 --> 00:11:22,390
- Heard some paroled ex-cons

255
00:11:22,440 --> 00:11:23,870
went shopping without
their wallets.

256
00:11:23,920 --> 00:11:26,140
- OG meta-criminals, actually.

257
00:11:26,180 --> 00:11:29,570
Jack, Ten, King, and the Queen,

258
00:11:29,620 --> 00:11:31,880
call themselves
the Royal Flush Gang.

259
00:11:31,920 --> 00:11:34,360
They were Central City's
very first meta-threat.

260
00:11:34,410 --> 00:11:35,410
- You work that case, too?

261
00:11:35,450 --> 00:11:36,970
- Actually, no.

262
00:11:37,020 --> 00:11:39,280
The first time
they pulled a job, I was...

263
00:11:43,810 --> 00:11:46,070
Kind of under the weather.

264
00:11:46,110 --> 00:11:47,680
It's weird. Their MO is

265
00:11:47,720 --> 00:11:51,340
stealing cash from casinos,
not microchips.

266
00:11:52,510 --> 00:11:54,250
- Well, at least no one
was killed.

267
00:11:55,300 --> 00:11:56,340
This time.

268
00:11:57,340 --> 00:11:58,690
- Everything okay, Captain?

269
00:12:01,560 --> 00:12:03,130
- This is the kind of case

270
00:12:03,170 --> 00:12:05,260
the meta-task force
would've been assigned to.

271
00:12:06,260 --> 00:12:10,530
- Um, so your mimic powers--

272
00:12:10,570 --> 00:12:12,840
how exactly do they work?

273
00:12:12,880 --> 00:12:15,360
- They only activate
in times of stress,

274
00:12:15,400 --> 00:12:18,280
when my adrenaline spikes,
and the effects are temporary.

275
00:12:19,190 --> 00:12:22,240
- That's good to--yeah.

276
00:12:23,630 --> 00:12:25,330
- Allen, does me being a meta

277
00:12:25,370 --> 00:12:27,330
make working for me
more difficult?

278
00:12:28,150 --> 00:12:29,810
- No, ma'am.

279
00:12:29,850 --> 00:12:31,940
It's already tough enough
as it is.

280
00:12:34,680 --> 00:12:37,250
I'll let you know
as soon as I find something.

281
00:12:37,290 --> 00:12:38,600
- Good.

282
00:12:42,520 --> 00:12:44,210
- [sighs]

283
00:12:44,260 --> 00:12:47,780
- So I've gone over everyone's
ideas, and they're great,

284
00:12:47,830 --> 00:12:49,260
but what I'd like to do
is start

285
00:12:49,310 --> 00:12:51,480
with last night's break-in
at Mercury Labs.

286
00:12:51,530 --> 00:12:53,610
[scoffs and groaning]

287
00:12:53,660 --> 00:12:56,400
- It's not news,
not in this city.

288
00:12:56,440 --> 00:12:59,660
- It's a high-tech theft
at a huge R&D corporation.

289
00:12:59,710 --> 00:13:01,580
- Which happens
all the time in this town.

290
00:13:01,620 --> 00:13:03,800
Was anyone killed...
- No.

291
00:13:03,840 --> 00:13:05,240
- Was the Flash involved...
- No, he isn't.

292
00:13:05,280 --> 00:13:06,630
- Tragedy sells papers, folks.
- But--

293
00:13:06,670 --> 00:13:08,760
- Sorry.
- That's not the point.

294
00:13:08,800 --> 00:13:10,070
- We should look into
the rumors of embezzlement

295
00:13:10,110 --> 00:13:11,680
inside the mayor's office.

296
00:13:11,720 --> 00:13:13,420
Scooping a major scandal
before our competition...

297
00:13:13,460 --> 00:13:15,070
- Will make Iris happy.

298
00:13:15,110 --> 00:13:16,460
Get in touch with someone
at the mayor's office.

299
00:13:16,510 --> 00:13:17,940
- I got 1,000 words to finish

300
00:13:17,990 --> 00:13:19,160
on the Sharks' new GM
for Iris, too.

301
00:13:19,210 --> 00:13:20,820
- Wait, what 1,000 words?

302
00:13:20,860 --> 00:13:22,770
- Well, I know the mayor's
executive assistant.

303
00:13:22,820 --> 00:13:24,120
We were in the same undergrad
sorority...

304
00:13:24,170 --> 00:13:25,780
- I need someone on this
Mercury break-in.

305
00:13:25,820 --> 00:13:27,300
- So she'll tell me everything.
- Uh, Vanya,

306
00:13:27,340 --> 00:13:29,220
I really need you to run
with this tech heist.

307
00:13:30,610 --> 00:13:33,180
- I'm gonna follow up on the
Calvert collision this morning.

308
00:13:33,220 --> 00:13:35,050
My source in
the county planner's office

309
00:13:35,090 --> 00:13:37,960
says it's gonna cost several
million to repair the damage.

310
00:13:38,010 --> 00:13:39,400
Talk about a budget crisis.

311
00:13:39,440 --> 00:13:42,450
Plus, that is what
Iris would want.

312
00:13:42,490 --> 00:13:47,190
- Iri--hold on.
Wait, you guys.

313
00:13:47,230 --> 00:13:48,670
Seriously?

314
00:13:51,670 --> 00:13:54,110
- We found this
at the train collision site.

315
00:13:54,150 --> 00:13:55,680
- I thought Kramer
had you working

316
00:13:55,720 --> 00:13:57,810
on the Mercury heist instead?

317
00:13:57,850 --> 00:13:59,810
- Uh, yeah. I am.
- You are,

318
00:13:59,860 --> 00:14:03,730
but you think that it's related
to the Calvert train collision?

319
00:14:03,770 --> 00:14:05,430
- I will know in a minute.

320
00:14:05,470 --> 00:14:08,210
While working evidence
from the Mercury Labs heist,

321
00:14:08,250 --> 00:14:10,950
I found charred marks
on the guard's weapons,

322
00:14:11,000 --> 00:14:13,390
marks exactly like those.

323
00:14:13,430 --> 00:14:15,910
Yeah, I was right.

324
00:14:15,960 --> 00:14:17,570
Heat signature's the same

325
00:14:17,610 --> 00:14:19,740
as the burn marks on
the weapons at Mercury Labs.

326
00:14:19,790 --> 00:14:23,140
Laser burns delivered
with pinpoint precision,

327
00:14:23,180 --> 00:14:24,710
Jack's trademarks.

328
00:14:24,750 --> 00:14:26,580
- Okay, okay.

329
00:14:26,620 --> 00:14:29,150
Even if it is
the Royal Flush Gang

330
00:14:29,190 --> 00:14:31,060
behind all of this, why?

331
00:14:31,100 --> 00:14:33,110
Why would they
go through all the trouble

332
00:14:33,150 --> 00:14:36,240
of causing
a massive railway collision

333
00:14:36,280 --> 00:14:38,500
when they haven't
even stolen anything yet?

334
00:14:38,550 --> 00:14:40,200
- I asked myself that, too.

335
00:14:40,240 --> 00:14:43,160
Then I found out what was
being carried in this case.

336
00:14:43,200 --> 00:14:45,860
A bleeding-edge beryllium core

337
00:14:45,900 --> 00:14:49,380
which is a highly unstable
power source.

338
00:14:49,430 --> 00:14:50,780
- And that's what caused
the trains to explode.

339
00:14:50,820 --> 00:14:52,950
- No.
A beryllium-based detonation

340
00:14:53,000 --> 00:14:55,300
would've leveled
a surrounding 10-mile radius.

341
00:14:56,610 --> 00:14:58,260
- [gasp]

342
00:14:58,300 --> 00:15:00,050
The core wasn't in the case
when the trains collided.

343
00:15:00,090 --> 00:15:02,570
- Which means,
the real question is,

344
00:15:02,610 --> 00:15:04,140
why is the Royal Flush Gang

345
00:15:04,180 --> 00:15:05,960
changing their MO
to become tech thieves?

346
00:15:06,010 --> 00:15:07,490
[door creaks]

347
00:15:10,970 --> 00:15:12,840
Korber, what's going on?

348
00:15:12,880 --> 00:15:15,020
- Iron Heights just lost power
for three seconds,

349
00:15:15,060 --> 00:15:17,500
during which every cell door
unlocked and opened.

350
00:15:17,540 --> 00:15:20,150
Now they've got 1,000 inmates
roaming the facility.

351
00:15:20,200 --> 00:15:22,720
- Barry, if they get out...
- Yeah, I know.

352
00:15:22,760 --> 00:15:27,250
♪

353
00:15:27,290 --> 00:15:28,510
- Barry, what happened?

354
00:15:28,550 --> 00:15:31,600
[men shouting]

355
00:15:32,820 --> 00:15:34,510
- I got the inmates back
in their cells

356
00:15:34,560 --> 00:15:36,210
before anyone got hurt,

357
00:15:36,260 --> 00:15:38,390
but we've got a bigger problem.

358
00:15:39,610 --> 00:15:42,260
Looks like the Royal Flush Gang
just leveled up too.

359
00:15:42,310 --> 00:15:44,700
♪

360
00:15:48,270 --> 00:15:50,010
- Well, I am impressed.

361
00:15:50,050 --> 00:15:51,440
A schedule,
timed to the minute,

362
00:15:51,490 --> 00:15:54,400
including a coffee stop
to recharge.

363
00:15:54,450 --> 00:15:57,230
Best handler ever.

364
00:15:57,280 --> 00:15:58,580
- Oh, you're getting
a whole lot more

365
00:15:58,630 --> 00:16:00,150
than java in Jitters,
my friend.

